ant part of a probable longer narrative written in the style of the Decameron. While employing some of those same gender and role reversals as Urania, including the privileging of heroic constancy in both men and women, it chronicles the tribulations that a couple undergoes until their secret marriage is publicly recognized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aItalian literaturey16th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  awomen writers, gender, female authors, novella, literature, jealousy, passion, depression, melancholy, feminism, love triangle, betrayal, adventure, travel narrative, crossdressing, role reversal, heroism, constancy, fidelity, marriage, secrecy, renaissance, italy, duchess, disguise, woman question, romance, unrequited, relationships, trust, intimacy.1 aFinucci, Valeria.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226048796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226048796/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles